<TITLE> North Sea oil platform evacuated after fire </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A North Sea oil platform was being evacuated on Sunday after a fire broke out on board the rig, rescue officials said. It is operated by Swedish-based Lundin Petroleum. Forty-four of the 159 people on board the Thistle Alpha have so far been evacuated from the rig, Royal Air Force (RAF) spokesman Michael Mulford told BBC television, adding there were no reports of casualties. Seven rescue helicopters were sent to the scene. Smoke and flames were seen on the platform, situated 120 miles (190 km) northeast of Shetland in Scotland. "At the last count they have lifted off 44 guys off. The plan is to evacuate all 159," Mulford told BBC television. "They have gone for a fairly major airlift from the first moment." "It would certainly appear to be a serious situation at this point," he said. "At the moment there are no reports of casualties." "The weather conditions are not great. There is a strong northwesterly wind blowing." A spokeswoman for the coastguards said: "There are 159 platform crew who are currently being evacuated by helicopter to neighbouring platforms. The on-board fire team is working to extinguish the fire." Oil and gas firm Lundin Petroleum said earlier in the month it had secured $1 billion in financing for exploration activities and possible acquisitio
